{"id":"1701.06954","submitter":"Jason Semeraro BA MPhil DPhil","authors":"Peter J. Cameron and Jason Semeraro","title":"The cycle polynomial of a permutation group","comments":"16 pages","journal-ref":"Electronic J. Combinatorics 25(1) (2018), Paper P1.14","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The cycle polynomial of a finite permutation group $G$ is the generating\nfunction for the number of elements of $G$ with a given number of cycles:\n\\[F_G(x) = \\sum_{g\\in G}x^{c(g)},\\] where $c(g)$ is the number of cycles of $g$\non $\\Omega$. In the first part of the paper, we develop basic properties of\nthis polynomial, and give a number of examples.\n  In the 1970s, Richard Stanley introduced the notion of reciprocity for pairs\nof combinatorial polynomials. We show that, in a considerable number of cases,\nthere is a polynomial in the reciprocal relation to the cycle polynomial of\n$G$; this is the orbital chromatic polynomial of $\\Gamma$ and $G$, where\n$\\Gamma$ is a $G$-invariant graph, introduced by the first author, Jackson and\nRudd. We pose the general problem of finding all such reciprocal pairs, and\ngive a number of examples and characterisations: the latter include the cases\nwhere $\\Gamma$ is a complete or null graph or a tree.\n  The paper concludes with some comments on other polynomials associated with a\npermutation group.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 24 Jan 2017 16:09:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-31"}
