mension $3+1/40$, and in particular this\nimplies that every Kakeya set in $\\mathbb{R}^4$ must have Hausdorff dimension\nat least $3+1/40$. This would be an improvement over the current best bound of\n3, which was established by Wolff in 1995.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 24 Jan 2017 19:18:14 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 15 Jan 2018 22:47:15 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 19 Apr 2019 22:28:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-23"}
