{"id":"1701.07155","submitter":"Kisielewicz Andrzej","authors":"Andrzej P. Kisielewicz","title":"Towards Resolving Keller's Cube Tiling Conjecture in Dimension Seven","comments":"33 pages, 5 figures, 2 tables","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.MG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A cube tiling of $\\mathbb{R}^d$ is a family of pairwise disjoint cubes\n$[0,1)^d+T=\\{[0,1)^d+t\\colon t\\in T\\}$ such that $\\bigcup_{t\\in\nT}([0,1)^d+t)=\\mathbb{R}^d$. Two cubes $[0,1)^d+t$, $[0,1)^d+s$ are called a\ntwin pair if $|t_j-s_j|=1$ for some $j\\in [d]=\\{1,\\ldots, d\\}$ and $t_i=s_i$\nfor every $i\\in [d]\\setminus \\{j\\}$. In $1930$, Keller conjectured that in\nevery cube tiling of $\\mathbb{R}^d$ there is a twin pair. Keller's conjecture\nis true for dimensions $d\\leq 6$ and false for all dimensions $d\\geq 8$. For\n$d=7$ the conjecture is still open. Let $x\\in \\mathbb{R}^d$, $i\\in [d]$, and\nlet $L(T,x,i)$ be the set of all $i$th coordinates $t_i$ of vectors $t\\in T$\nsuch that $([0,1)^d+t)\\cap ([0,1]^d+x)\\neq \\emptyset$ and $t_i\\leq x_i$. Let\n$r^-(T)=\\min_{x\\in \\mathbb{R}^d}\\; \\max_{1\\leq i\\leq d}|L(T,x,i)|$ and\n$r^+(T)=\\max_{x\\in \\mathbb{R}^d}\\; \\max_{1\\leq i\\leq d}|L(T,x,i)|$. It is known\nthat if $r^-(T)\\leq 2$ or $r^+(T)\\geq 5$, then Keller's conjecture is true for\n$d=7$. In the paper we show that it is also true for $d=7$ if $r^+(T)=4$. Thus,\nif $[0,1)^7+T$ is a counterexample to Keller's conjecture, then $r^+(T)=3$,\nwhich is the last unsolved case of Keller's conjecture. Additionally, a new\nproof of Keller's conjecture in dimensions $d\\leq 6$ is given.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 25 Jan 2017 04:36:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-01-26"}
